WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:10.960
Hi, everyone. I'm Gagandeep Singh, and I'm joined by my colleague, Xu Fei. We are solutions

00:00:10.960 --> 00:00:15.920
engineers at RStudio, soon to be called Posit. And we are here to answer a question that

00:00:15.920 --> 00:00:20.879
we get asked a lot, which is, can you use Python with RStudio Team? And the answer is,

00:00:20.879 --> 00:00:25.080
of course, yes, you can. Very recently, I had to answer this question, so I'm going

00:00:25.080 --> 00:00:29.799
to start by sharing a story with you. I'm an Indian national. In order to be here in

00:00:29.799 --> 00:00:34.040
the U.S. to attend this conference, I need to get a visa. And as part of the immigration

00:00:34.040 --> 00:00:37.759
process, I have to get an interview with an officer, where they ask you questions like,

00:00:37.759 --> 00:00:43.040
where are you going? What will you be doing? So I told them that I'm going to this conference,

00:00:43.040 --> 00:00:48.000
I'm giving a talk about using Python with RStudio. The officer said, oh, I know Python,

00:00:48.000 --> 00:00:55.080
but I didn't know you could use it with RStudio. Well, I told him that's exactly what my talk

00:00:55.080 --> 00:01:01.639
is about. Unfortunately, officer Johnson could not be here with us today. But if you're

00:01:01.639 --> 00:01:07.839
in the audience, we are assuming that you're a multilingual data scientist who has access

00:01:07.839 --> 00:01:13.120
to RStudio products and wants to use Python with them. Or you are an R user who works

00:01:13.120 --> 00:01:18.080
with a lot of Python colleagues, and you may or may not have access to our products, but

00:01:18.080 --> 00:01:21.519
you're looking for ways to collaborate with them.

00:01:21.519 --> 00:01:26.480
So it is one thing to say that you can use Python in RStudio products. We're here to

00:01:26.480 --> 00:01:32.320
show you how it works with a use case. We're in the D.C. area right now, and there is an

00:01:32.320 --> 00:01:37.559
active bike share program outside called Capital Bike Share. We went out and took the picture

00:01:37.559 --> 00:01:43.599
yesterday, and this is the station right outside of the hotel. As you can see, there are bikes

00:01:43.599 --> 00:01:49.339
docked into the bike station. When you go to the company's website, you will see a map

00:01:49.339 --> 00:01:52.540
that shows you all the bike stations. When you click on one of the stations, it will

00:01:52.540 --> 00:01:57.459
show you how many bikes are available right now from a live data feed.

00:01:57.459 --> 00:02:02.300
Now, what it doesn't tell you is how many bikes are going to be available in the future.

00:02:02.300 --> 00:02:09.300
As we know, the bike availability varies a lot by the time of day, the location, and

00:02:09.300 --> 00:02:13.619
we, if we want to have a smooth trip experience, we want to be able to predict how many bikes

00:02:13.619 --> 00:02:19.020
are going to be available in the future. So because there's a live data feed, we can

00:02:19.020 --> 00:02:23.779
actually grab the data, store it somewhere, and make a predictive model so that we can

00:02:23.779 --> 00:02:26.380
actually know how many bikes are going to be available in the future. So that's what

00:02:26.380 --> 00:02:29.979
we want to do. If you were here at the very conference back

00:02:29.979 --> 00:02:36.220
in 2020, you probably have seen a talk that uses the similar data set, does everything

00:02:36.220 --> 00:02:42.899
in R packages. It's actually from our colleague Alex. So this project has been successfully

00:02:42.899 --> 00:02:47.580
running for over two years. So a lot of data has been processed and stored as interoperable

00:02:47.580 --> 00:02:52.460
data assets that we'll get back to in a second. And there's a lot of data being stored and

00:02:52.460 --> 00:02:56.259
processed. When I joined the company last year from more

00:02:56.259 --> 00:03:01.100
of a Python data science background, Gagan and I started talking. So since we have all

00:03:01.100 --> 00:03:05.020
these data, can we do something different? Can we do something entirely in Python and

00:03:05.020 --> 00:03:12.179
using our pro products? And we wanted to do this for two reasons. Number one, well, just

00:03:12.179 --> 00:03:17.300
because we can, why not? Well, that's not really a good reason. The second reason is

00:03:17.300 --> 00:03:24.020
actually we thought this could be a very common scenario where in our pro product customers,

00:03:24.020 --> 00:03:27.779
the teams that work in one language may want to collaborate with another team in a different

00:03:27.779 --> 00:03:36.339
language using interoperable data assets that's completely deployed in the pro product ecosystem.

00:03:36.339 --> 00:03:41.779
So we are also thinking that the conference is going to be in D.C., so we actually get

00:03:41.779 --> 00:03:46.660
to go to D.C. and ride those bikes. And here we are.

00:03:46.660 --> 00:03:52.779
So let's recap the workflow for the bike prediction use case. As in with any other project, it

00:03:52.779 --> 00:03:56.979
starts with the data source, which in this case is the capital bike share API, and the

00:03:56.979 --> 00:04:03.500
data is refreshed every day. Then the objective is to import this data, transform it, and

00:04:03.500 --> 00:04:08.940
save it either in a database or an interoperable data asset like bins, so based on the frequency

00:04:08.940 --> 00:04:13.820
of the update. Then we have to consume this data, build a prediction model to show the

00:04:13.820 --> 00:04:18.339
number of bikes for each bike station. Then we have to move this model to a deployable

00:04:18.339 --> 00:04:22.260
location where the output, the predictions of the number of bikes can be shared with

00:04:22.260 --> 00:04:27.820
other applications. And speaking of other applications, we have to build a way to share

00:04:27.820 --> 00:04:34.380
the predictions with our users. As in with the previous talk, this work is already available

00:04:34.380 --> 00:04:40.459
and running successfully all in R. So Shufay and I, when we were looking at this use case,

00:04:40.459 --> 00:04:45.739
we realized that we have access to this data already in the form of the database and the

00:04:45.739 --> 00:04:51.220
bins that the R ETL process is updating. So we decided to, in order to address the needs

00:04:51.220 --> 00:04:55.739
of a team which uses a similar workflow, where part of the workflow is in one language and

00:04:55.739 --> 00:04:59.859
part of the workflow is in another language, we decided that we'll build the model, build

00:04:59.859 --> 00:05:04.700
the dashboards in Python, all within our RStudio products.

00:05:04.700 --> 00:05:10.820
So let's take a look at the application itself. So this is developed in Shiny for Python,

00:05:10.820 --> 00:05:15.299
as you heard yesterday, deployed on RStudio Connect, which we'll get into in a second.

00:05:15.299 --> 00:05:20.100
You see a map of the DC area, and there are circles with numbers in them. These represent

00:05:20.100 --> 00:05:24.500
this cluster of bike stations. If you click into it, it zooms in, and eventually we'll

00:05:24.500 --> 00:05:28.500
see blue circles that represent the stations themselves. The bigger the circle, the more

00:05:28.500 --> 00:05:31.980
bikes that are available, and if you click on one of the circles, it's going to give

00:05:31.980 --> 00:05:38.660
you the predictive graph of the number of bikes available in the next 24 hours.

00:05:38.660 --> 00:05:45.579
So you heard of RStudio team and RStudio professional products, and how does ‑‑ what are they?

00:05:45.579 --> 00:05:50.859
And why do we need them? And how does Python fit in here? RStudio team is actually an umbrella

00:05:50.859 --> 00:05:57.059
term for three professional products, namely Workbench, Connect, and Package Manager.

00:05:57.059 --> 00:06:01.420
As Python data scientists, we need a place to start writing our project in code, and

00:06:01.420 --> 00:06:06.339
we need an environment to code. And so Workbench offers a centralized server‑based environment

00:06:06.339 --> 00:06:12.579
that allows you to code in your favorite data science IDEs, so Jupyter and VS Code.

00:06:12.579 --> 00:06:18.739
As your project matures, you may want to start sharing your content and deploy it somewhere,

00:06:18.739 --> 00:06:23.540
and that's where your RStudio Connect comes in handy. It's designed exactly for that,

00:06:23.540 --> 00:06:30.619
and allows you to deploy a very wide variety of data science assets, especially the interoperable

00:06:30.619 --> 00:06:37.339
ones, such as pins, APIs, and reports like Quartel and Jupyter notebooks, and interactive

00:06:37.339 --> 00:06:42.140
dashboards like Plotly Dash, Streamlit, and, of course, our favorite and the latest, Shiny

00:06:42.140 --> 00:06:46.700
for Python. And if you want to install packages into a

00:06:46.700 --> 00:06:52.059
centralized location, and that's not directly from PyPI, you can use Package Manager for

00:06:52.059 --> 00:06:57.339
that. So what are we going to show you in the next

00:06:57.339 --> 00:07:01.339
few minutes is that we're going to show you a workflow from developing the model using

00:07:01.339 --> 00:07:07.220
existing interoperable data objects in the Workbench, and we'll deploy that to Connect,

00:07:07.220 --> 00:07:11.500
and I'll come back and visit the application itself, we'll make a change, and we'll update

00:07:11.500 --> 00:07:15.260
it live to the Connect deployment.

00:07:15.260 --> 00:07:21.179
So let's see the demo. As Shufei mentioned, we're going to start with, like, we already

00:07:21.179 --> 00:07:25.140
have access to the data, so we're going to start with the model building process. So

00:07:25.140 --> 00:07:31.019
in order for me to start working, I need access to the IDE, so I go to our demo Workbench,

