and it's converting this function into a fast, converting this model into a fast API and

00:10:08.039 --> 00:10:13.159
directly deploying it on my RStudio Connect instance. So you can see, right, like from

00:10:13.159 --> 00:10:19.039
a few lines of code, under 10 lines of code, I was able to move this model from my notebook

00:10:19.039 --> 00:10:24.440
into Connect using Vetiver. So I've done the deployment to save us time here. Let's

00:10:24.440 --> 00:10:30.119
see what the deployment looks like. So this is my deployed model as a fast API onto RStudio

00:10:30.119 --> 00:10:36.880
Connect. So I get access to these docs that the fast API provides. I can see the API URL.

00:10:36.880 --> 00:10:41.239
I can see what kind of features it's taking. I can make a sample prediction. I can play

00:10:41.239 --> 00:10:47.960
with it here. As this API is running on RStudio Connect, I get access to all these features,

00:10:47.960 --> 00:10:52.479
which is what Connect provides. So I can decide who I want to share this API with.

00:10:52.479 --> 00:10:57.679
I can change the runtime credentials for this API. I can manage it here.

00:10:57.679 --> 00:11:05.000
What I've done so far is run the model once on the current state of the database, but

00:11:05.000 --> 00:11:10.479
the R process is updating this database every day because the number of bikes are changing

